Polish Stocks: BRE Bank, KGHM, Orlen, Pekao, PKO Bank Shares

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-04-18T16:12:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/polish-stocks-orlen-pekao-pko-bank-shares-move-in-warsaw.html
Poland ’s WIG20 Index fell the most
in two months, declining 44.51, or 1.5 percent, to 2,872.70 at
the 5:30 p.m. close in Warsaw.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
 Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.  PKO Bank Polski SA (PKO PW), Poland’s biggest bank, lost
1.63 zloty, or 3.5 percent, to 44.62 zloty.  Bank Pekao SA (PEO)  , the second-largest bank, slid 2.7 zloty, or 1.5 percent, to
173.3 zloty and  BRE Bank SA (BRE)  , a unit of Commerzbank AG,
declined 7 zloty, or 2 percent, to 340 zloty.  Banks dropped across Europe after Standard & Poor’s Ratings
Service revised its credit outlook for the U.S. to “negative”
and speculation escalated that Greece needs to restructure its
debt.  KGHM Polska Miedz SA (KGH)  , the copper producer with the
biggest European mine output, sank 5.5 zloty, or 2.8 percent, to
188.2 zloty, falling the most in more than a month as the price
of the metal declined.  PKN Orlen SA (PKN PW), Poland’s biggest oil company, fell 1
zloty, or 1.8 percent, to 56.2 zloty. Oil tumbled for the first
time in four days in  New York  after Saudi Arabia, the world’s
biggest crude exporter, said the global market has enough oil to
meet demand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
